Zero Trust in practice means security decisions are continuously validated rather than assuming trust based on network location.

Practical examples include:

* Employees accessing finance systems must use MFA even from office networks
* Developers accessing production systems receive Just-In-Time privileged access
* Guest users are restricted to limited collaboration spaces
* Devices must meet compliance policies before accessing sensitive apps

For example, a remote employee logging in from a personal laptop may be blocked unless the device meets compliance standards.

A real-life use case is global enterprises protecting intellectual property while supporting hybrid work.

Another example is hospitals requiring explicit identity checks before accessing patient records.

Zero Trust shifts security from location-based trust to identity, device, and context verification.
